{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n`_mkdir_lock_is_stale` (`src/rebar/_store/lock.py:169-188`) has branches for read errors\n(`except OSError: return False`), missing separator, foreign host, non-int PID\n(`except ValueError: return False`), and live/dead PID. Existing tests cover dead/live/\nabsent/foreign-host, but the **non-int PID, missing-`:`-separator, and owner-file read-error**\nbranches are untested (PARTIALLY-VALIDATED: a real partial-branch coverage gap). The safety\nproperty is conservative — none of these may cause reclamation.\n\n## What\nAdd a single table-driven test over the malformed/unreadable owner-stamp forms, asserting\n`_mkdir_lock_is_stale` returns `False` (never reclaim) for each. Deterministic realizations of\nthe two racy cases:\n- **unreadable owner file** → put a DIRECTORY at the owner-file path so `open()` raises\n  `IsADirectoryError` (an `OSError`) → the `except OSError: return False` branch.\n- **owner file replaced/observed mid-write** → a partial stamp with the colon not yet written\n  (hostname only), i.e. the exact content a reader that caught the write in flight would see →\n  the missing-separator branch → `False`.\n\n## Scope\n- `tests/unit/test_lock_stale_reclaim.py` — one parametrized/table-driven test of the\n  malformed-stamp forms.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Table covers: empty owner file; missing colon; empty host; empty PID; non-numeric PID;\n      negative PID; zero PID; extra delimiters (`host:1:2`); foreign host; a directory in place\n      of the owner file (unreadable); and a partial mid-write stamp (colon not yet written).\n- [ ] Every case asserts `_mkdir_lock_is_stale(...) is False` — conservative, no reclamation.\n- [ ] `make test` green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783796994341855001,"uuid":"cd59c38f-a5c4-4e2c-b183-aa1764039ab1"}